                    <div class = "row">
                        <h3 class = "sub-sub-header">Part 3 - The Sights</h3>
                        <div class = "col-sm-6 col-sm-push-6 side-image-wrapper">
                            <figure>
                                <img class = "side-image" src = "images/glacier-point-story-image.jpg" alt = "Placeholder">
                                <figcaption>via <a href = "https://travel.usnews.com/Yosemite_CA/Things_To_Do/Glacier_Point_Trail_Hike_59152/">usnews.com</a></figcaption>
                            </figure>
                        </div>
                        <div class = "col-sm-6 col-sm-pull-6 main-info">
                            <p>
                                So, being the person who goes on an adventure with no plan on how to efficiently see everything Yosemite has to offer, I was at quite the crossroads when attempting to decide where I wanted to go first. I eventually decided to head up towards the upper portion of Yosemite Falls since that was the closest attraction to me upon arriving. It was a couple mile hike to the top taking the Yosemite Falls Trailhead but I eventually made it towards the top. It was worth the hike because the view from the top was astonishing. Since I had been travelling a lot in the first day, I called it quits since the hike was challenging and travelling generally just tires me out. The next day I planned to see the Bridal Veil Falls, El Capitan, and Glacier Point. I woke up early on the second day as to give myself enough time to see all three attractions that I had planned the day prior. I first headed for Glacier Point, which looking back on it now, it was a terrible first adventure as the trail was a whopping four miles uphill just to get to the viewpoint. Once I was at the top, it was one of the most beautiful views I’ve seen in my entire life. It was almost as if you could see so far that you would think the earth was a flat expansion for hundreds of miles. Needless to say, I took a shuttle back into the valley and I was able to stop by Bridalveil Fall and El Capitan on the way back. These places weren’t as crazy of a walk to gain access to. Bridalveil Fall was a short walk right off the road from where I originally came in to the park and El Capitan was another short walk in the opposite direction. After another successful day of seeing the sights, I had dinner at the Mountain Room Restaurant & Lounge where I ordered the Filet Mignon mid-rare. On the third day, it was time for me to leave the valley to catch my flight that wasn’t until later in the evening so I had some time to see a couple more attractions on my way out. I’d looked up what was called the Tunnel View in Yosemite National Park because it one of the more famous spots for people to take pictures and I figured it was a great sight to see on my way out of the park. The other place that I wanted to check out before I left were the famous giant sequoias in Mariposa Grove. Sadly, I heard that Mariposa Grove was closed at the time that I wanted to see it and I didn’t have enough to time to wait for it to open because my flight was leaving that night.
                            </p>
